      <field name="heading_text">AFTER THE RAIN.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">After the Rain Image of the text page, with illustration in the left border</field>
      <field name="fulltext">IT had rained all night, but the sun shone in the morning. The cottage-roofs steamed in the sun; the roses in the garden were still heavy with rain and draggled with garden-mold; the wet trees gave out green lights; little rain-pools shone in the road like liquid gold, and the sparrows dipped in them. It had rained all night, but the sun shone in the morning.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">The lover whom love had forsaken looked out of his window. All night had he lain awake, listening to the rain on the roof, and longing for his lost love, while the memory of her caresses clung to his soul as sweet and evasive as the perfume of the roses in the garden.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">It had rained all night, but the sun shone in the morning. The lover whom love had forsaken looked out of his window. "My love has forsaken me," he said, "but it has stopped raining."</field>
      <field name="fulltext">Mary E. Wilkins.</field>
